      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bad Doctors Get a Free Ride,'' by Sidney M. Wolfe (Op-Ed, March 4):</p>
        <p>All of us in the practice of medicine, like our patients, must pay for the malpractice of a relative few.</p>
        <p>State medical boards must, as Dr. Wolfe suggests, reconsider their leniency toward recidivists.</p>
        <p>But his call for public access to the national practitioner data bank is questionable. Even competent, caring doctors are sued as part of the litigation merry-go-round that now characterizes the relationship among disappointed patients, the plaintiff's bar and the doctor.</p>
        <p>Many doctors settle these cases, some under pressure from their own insurer, to put the unpleasantness behind them. This occurs even when cases lack merit. Clearly, much of the information in the data bank cannot be read as an indicator of competence.</p>
        <p>PAUL BLOUSTEIN, M.D.  Cincinnati, March 5, 2003</p>
      </block>
